INSERT INTO pjc_presentations VALUES("11","2014-12-22 00:00:00","201412223142","nikuss","methodology","2015-01-29","11:00,12:30","An introduction to linear and generalized linear mixed-effects models in R","Matteo Lisi","Mixed-effects models provide a flexible and powerful tool to analyze grouped data (e.g., longitudinal design, repeated measures). Linear mixed-effects models can handle easily specific designs that are more difficult to analyze with classical ANOVA models, for example when within-subjects predictors includes both categorical and continuous variables, when there are continuous covariates that vary on a trial-by-trial basis, or in the case of crossed random effects, such as subjects and items (e.g., images, words, sentences). Generalized linear mixed-effects models can be particularly useful in the case  of within-subjects designs with binomial or proportional dependent variables (e.g. response accuracy). Finally, they provide an alternative approach (with higher statistical power) to the two-level analysis typically adopted in psychophysics experiments (where in the first level psychometric functions are fitted separately for each participant, and in the second level individual estimates are used as input for group analysis).nnIn this tutorial I will briefly present the theory and go through some examples, to show how to fit such models in the open-source software R using the lme4 library (http://cran.r-project.org/web/packages/lme4/). nn","nikuss","1");
INSERT INTO pjc_presentations VALUES("13","2015-01-12 00:00:00","201501124284","hmk","research","2015-02-05","11:00,12:30","FlashDrag and SoundDrag","","Flash-drag, flash-grab, flash-lag (repeat this out loud three times please) are all examples that demonstrate motion extrapolation. Does motion extrapolation also occur for auditory stimuli? We used ILD sweeps that moved from right to left or vice versa, interrupted the sweep with a 5ms gap and asked our subjects to localize the position of the gap. Similar to reports of flash drag, subjects consistently reported the position of the gap to appear further in the direction of motion. This finding points to a common mechanism for auditory and visual modalities that accounts for motion extrapolation. ","hmk","1");
